<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="1303" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1303">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/36</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HMT1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-11">
                                <hi rend="italic">November 11, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5:40 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>267. Your 253, 10th. Foreign Office states that instructions have already
                            been sent French Minister at The Hague to offer no objection to transit
                            of foodstuffs through the Netherlands from United States destined to
                            Belgium. At Embassy’s request Foreign Office stated it would repeat
                            instructions to Minister at The Hague.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_HMT1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>